"""
MKT Context Commentary — Romans chapters 15–16
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-romans-15-16.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/romans.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/romans.json (MKT text for quoting)
- data/commentary/ellicott/romans.json (philological and historical notes)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch15 continues the weak/strong food controversy from ch14; context entries
  identify the weak as predominantly returning Jewish believers (expelled under
  Claudius, c.AD 49, now returning) and the strong as Gentile or hellenized
  Jewish believers. The social tension was real and present in the congregation.
- The priestly metaphor in 15:16 (leitourgos, hierourgountas, prosphora) is
  treated as deliberate cultic language casting the Gentile mission in temple
  categories — the Gentiles become the sacrificial offering Paul presents to God.
- The Jerusalem collection (15:25-27) is treated as a deliberate solidarity act
  and debt-payment gesture, not merely charity; Paul's theological and social
  rationale are foregrounded.
- Ch16's greeting list is treated as a sociological window: the names span
  slaves, freedpersons, women with leadership roles, house-church networks,
  and Jewish returnees. Erastus (16:23) is cross-referenced with the Corinthian
  inscription.
- Junia (16:7) is treated as a woman's name (the dominant scholarly reading) and
  the debate over en tois apostolois is presented without forcing one conclusion.
- "Consistent terminology" carried from prior scripts: "Paul" not "the Apostle";
  honor-shame and patron-client frameworks; Second Temple Jewish context named.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ROMANS = {
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>The "strong" and "weak" categories continue directly from chapter 14. In the Roman congregation, the "strong" almost certainly included Gentile believers and hellenized Jewish Christians who felt no obligation to observe kashrut or holy-day regulations, while the "weak" were predominantly Jewish believers who had recently returned to Rome after Claudius\'s expulsion edict (c.AD 49). Those returnees had likely maintained Jewish dietary practice while away and brought those scruples back with them. The division was not merely theological — it was a social fault-line between two communities with different ethnic histories and different relations to the Torah.</p><p>Paul\'s instruction to "bear the failings of the weak" uses <em>bastazein</em>, a verb of carrying a burden. The same verb appears in Gal 6:2 ("bear one another\'s burdens"). The instruction is asymmetrical: the strong bear, the weak do not bear in return. This is not because the weak are right, but because social repair in a hierarchy of the strong and weak always requires initiative from those with greater capacity.</p>',
    "2": '<p><em>Oikodomē</em> (edification) is an architectural metaphor: constructing a building. Paul consistently uses it for the social-spiritual growth of the community as a whole (1 Cor 14:3,5; Eph 4:29). "Building up the neighbor" reframes the strong person\'s freedom: the question is not "what can I do?" but "what does this action do to the communal structure?" In the honor-shame world of first-century Rome, this was a countercultural move — the socially elevated were expected to demonstrate their status, not subordinate their preferences to those beneath them on the social scale.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Paul\'s Christ-precedent cites Ps 69:9 ("The insults of those who insult you have fallen on me"), a psalm widely read in early Christianity as depicting the suffering of the righteous servant. The psalm was Davidic, and the pattern — the servant of God absorbing reproach directed at God — provided the early church with one of its primary templates for interpreting the passion. For the Roman congregation, invoking this psalm would have activated the whole register of the suffering Messiah: a figure who willingly bore what was not his to bear, precisely as Paul asks the strong to do.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The assertion that Scripture was written "for our instruction" reflects Jewish hermeneutical practice: Torah speaks to all generations, not only to the original recipients. The Mishnah formalizes this: "Turn it, and turn it again, for everything is in it" (Avot 5:22). The specific qualities named — endurance (<em>hypomonē</em>) and encouragement (<em>paraklēsis</em>) — are the virtues produced by extended engagement with Scripture. The Roman congregation, undergoing social stress from the strong/weak division as well as Roman imperial pressure, needed precisely these virtues. The Scriptures were not merely informational; they formed character across time.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The prayer for "the same mindedness" (<em>to auto phronein</em>) picks up Paul\'s signature unity language (cf. Phil 2:2, 4:2). The phrase "according to Christ Jesus" establishes the standard: not agreement on food laws or calendar, but a common orientation toward Christ. In the second-century church, this text would be read against the backdrop of liturgical unity — one Eucharist, one bishop, one mind. But Paul\'s immediate context is simpler and more urgent: can Jewish and Gentile believers eat together at the same table? The prayer is a pastoral wish that they can.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The climax of the extended argument begun in 14:1 is liturgical: Jews and Gentiles together, with one mouth, glorifying the God of Israel. This was not self-evident in a city where Jewish and Gentile worshippers had historically separate synagogal and cultic communities. The Roman synagogues were numerous (at least eleven are attested from inscriptions), each with distinct ethnic and geographic identities. The idea of a single community voice crossing those lines was a social achievement as much as a theological declaration. Paul\'s doxological goal is corporate worship that visibly unites the divided community.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The command "accept one another" (<em>proslambanesthe</em>) is the same verb used in 14:1 and 14:3 for accepting the weak and accepting each other across the food controversy. By now repeating it with Christ\'s reception of believers as the model, Paul closes the frame around the entire discussion of chapters 14–15. Christ\'s acceptance was unconditional — it did not wait for the believer to conform to the strong party\'s norms or the weak party\'s scruples. The social implication is direct: members of the congregation are not to make their acceptance of one another contingent on agreement about disputable practices.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The description of Christ as "a servant of the circumcision" (<em>diakonos peritoies</em>) on behalf of God\'s truth is precise and historically loaded. The circumcision represents Israel, the covenant people. Christ\'s mission to Israel was to confirm — not annul — the covenant promises to the patriarchs. For the Jewish believers in Rome, this was an affirmation that the gospel did not require them to abandon their covenant identity; rather, the promises made to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob had been kept in Christ. Paul defends the theological legitimacy of Jewish covenant membership within the new community.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The OT catena that follows (vv9-12) was likely drawn from early Christian liturgical and homiletical use — a collection of Gentile-inclusion texts that Paul and others had assembled as proof-texts for the universal scope of the gospel. The first citation (Ps 18:49, "I will praise you among the nations") places the praise of Israel\'s God on Gentile lips. In context, Ps 18 is a royal thanksgiving psalm; Paul reads it Christologically (Christ giving praise among the nations) and extends it to all who are in Christ. The citation introduces the theme of Gentile worship that the catena will develop through four increasingly explicit texts.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The second citation from Deut 32:43 (LXX) calls the nations to "rejoice with his people." Deuteronomy 32 is the Song of Moses — a covenantal poem that reviews Israel\'s history and pronounces judgment and salvation. The LXX version of 32:43 includes "his people" alongside "nations" in a way the Hebrew MT does not, making it more explicitly inclusive. Paul follows the LXX, as he consistently does with OT citations. For the Roman congregation, hearing Moses\'s Song cited in support of Gentile inclusion would have been theologically significant: the foundational covenantal text of Israel endorses Gentile participation.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The third citation (Ps 117:1) is the shortest psalm in the Hebrew Bible — two verses — and entirely devoted to calling all nations to praise the Lord. In Jewish liturgy, Psalm 117 was part of the Hallel collection (Pss 113-118) sung at Passover and other major festivals. Paul\'s Roman audience familiar with synagogue practice would have known it as a festal text. Its inclusion here is fitting: the Hallel was sung at the Last Supper (Matt 26:30), and the early Christian community likely continued using it in worship. Paul cites a text his hearers would have sung.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The fourth and climactic OT citation (Isa 11:10, "The Root of Jesse") is explicitly Messianic in its Isaiah context: the shoot from Jesse\'s stump will rule the nations and be a rallying point for them. Isaiah 11 was among the most-cited Messianic passages in Second Temple Judaism — the Dead Sea Scrolls (4QpIsa) apply it to the coming Davidic deliverer. Paul cites the LXX version, which adds "in him the nations will place their hope" (elpiousintas). This closes the catena with an explicitly eschatological note: the nations\' hope is located in the Davidic Messiah, and Christ fulfills that description.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The benediction "God of hope" (<em>ho theos tēs elpidos</em>) is unique to this verse in Paul\'s letters. It reflects the eschatological orientation of the preceding catena: the God who promised inclusion of the nations is the God whose promises are still outstanding, whose future is still arriving. Joy and peace as present-tense experiences of the Spirit are understood as firstfruits of the coming fullness — anticipations of what will be fully revealed. In the Jewish eschatological framework, these are messianic blessings: Isa 9:7 promises endless peace; Zeph 3:17 describes God rejoicing over his people. The Roman congregation receives these as present gifts.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Paul\'s self-deprecating affirmation of the Roman congregation\'s maturity serves an important rhetorical function: it explains why he has written such an extensive theological letter to a community he did not found. In the Roman patronage system, it was presumptuous to offer unsolicited instruction to those who had not sought your services and owed you no client-obligation. Paul preempts this objection by affirming they are fully capable of teaching one another (<em>nouthetein</em>, admonishing). His boldness in writing is not a claim of superiority but an exercise of his apostolic grace-gift, acknowledged and agreed upon as the basis for his writing.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The phrase "because of the grace God gave me" (<em>dia tēn charin tēn dotheisan moi</em>) echoes Romans 1:5 ("grace and apostleship"). Paul\'s claim to write boldly on some points rests not on personal authority but on a divinely assigned role. For the Jewish-Christian members of the Roman congregation who might question whether a Pharisee-turned-apostle had the right to instruct them, this appeal to divine commissioning was the relevant credential. The "reminding" (<em>epanamimnēskōn</em>) framing is characteristically modest: Paul is not teaching new things but recalling what they already know from the common apostolic tradition.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The priestly metaphor cluster here is dense and deliberate: <em>leitourgon</em> (a cultic minister, used of both priests and Levites in the LXX), <em>hierourgountas</em> (performing priestly service, a distinctly cultic term), and <em>prosphora</em> (offering, used of sacrificial oblations). Paul describes his apostolic ministry in the vocabulary of the Jerusalem temple: he is a priest of the gospel, and the Gentile converts are the sacrifice he offers up. This inversion is remarkable — the Gentiles were typically considered ritually impure and excluded from the inner courts of the temple. Paul\'s priestly language places them at the center of the divine offering, consecrated by the Holy Spirit as an acceptable <em>qorban</em> (offering).</p>',
    "17": '<p>The "boasting in Christ Jesus regarding the things pertaining to God" (<em>ta pros ton theon</em>) is a technical phrase for the sphere of priestly ministry — what is done before God in the cultic realm. Paul\'s boast is deliberately bounded: he claims no credit for human strategy or rhetorical skill, only for what Christ has accomplished through the priestly service of gospel proclamation. In a Roman culture saturated with competitive honor-claims and public recognition of achievements, Paul\'s restricted boast would have been conspicuous for what it does not claim.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"What Christ has accomplished through me" frames the entire missionary enterprise as Christ-agency through a human instrument. Paul lists "word and deed" — preaching and miracles — as the two channels of this agency. The category of "miracle-working apostle" was contested in the early church (cf. 2 Cor 12:12, where Paul defends his signs against those who question them). For the Roman congregation, which did not know Paul personally, this is a self-introduction as well as a theological claim: the Gentiles who obeyed the gospel did so because God was working through Paul, not merely because Paul was persuasive.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The geographic sweep "from Jerusalem to Illyricum" traces Paul\'s missionary arc. Jerusalem was the origin-point of the apostolic mission; Illyricum (the eastern Adriatic coast, modern Albania/Croatia) was the northwestern boundary of his known travel. The reference to "signs and wonders" (<em>sēmeia kai terata</em>) in this expansion recalls the language of Moses\'s and the Exodus (Deut 6:22; Acts 7:36) — the same divine-attestation pattern that validated the first covenant event now validates the new-covenant missionary advance. Paul implicitly presents himself as continuing a pattern established at Sinai.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The pioneer principle — "not building on another man\'s foundation" — reflects an informal territorial understanding within the early apostolic mission. Paul elsewhere describes Apollos as having "watered" what Paul "planted" (1 Cor 3:6), suggesting an understood sequence of founding and follow-on apostolic work. The principle may also reflect the Isaiah 52:15 citation Paul will use in v21: the Servant announces to those who had not heard — the frontiers, not the established centers. Paul sees himself as fulfilling the Servant\'s vocation by reaching the outermost regions of the Gentile world.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The Isa 52:15 citation ("Those who were not told about him will see") comes from the fourth Servant Song\'s closing verse, immediately before Isa 53. In context, it describes the reaction of kings who had not previously heard: astonishment and silence at the Servant\'s exaltation. Paul applies it to his own practice of going where Christ has not been named. The citation is unusual because Isa 52:15 was not, in Second Temple usage, a text specifically associated with the Gentile mission; Paul is reading it typologically — the Servant\'s mission to the speechless kings is now extended through Paul\'s mission to the unevangelized peoples.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Paul\'s repeated hindrance from coming to Rome (mentioned also in 1:13) is acknowledged again here. The reason he gives — "this is why I have often been prevented" — links his Rome-delay to the same pioneer principle just articulated: there was unfinished Gentile territory to cover in the East before he could turn West. For the Roman congregation, who might have wondered why the apostle to the Gentiles had never visited the capital city of the Gentile world, this provides the explanation. Paul was not avoiding Rome; he was completing the eastern arc before beginning the western.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"No more place for me in these regions" is a remarkable claim. Paul does not mean every person in the East has been evangelized, but that the primary centers — the regional capitals and crossroads cities — have been reached and communities established that can carry on the work. Ancient missionary strategy, like Roman administrative strategy, focused on urban centers from which influence would radiate to surrounding territories. Corinth, Ephesus, Philippi, Thessalonica — each was an urban hub. By establishing communities in these hubs, Paul considered the eastern mission structurally complete.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Spain (<em>Spania</em>) represented the western end of the known world in Roman geographical consciousness — the "Pillars of Hercules" (Strait of Gibraltar) beyond which lay Ocean. To reach Spain was to reach the edge of the <em>oikoumenē</em> (inhabited world). Paul\'s ambition to preach there reflects his eschatological framework: the gospel must reach the ends of the earth before the end (cf. Mark 13:10). The proposed stop at Rome "while passing through" reverses the normal role of Rome as center: for Paul, Rome is a waystation on the road to the western frontier, not the destination itself.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Paul was traveling to Jerusalem at the time of writing (c.AD 56-57, the end of his third missionary journey) carrying a collection from the Gentile churches of Macedonia and Achaia for the poor believers in Jerusalem. This project had consumed years and organizational effort (1 Cor 16:1-4; 2 Cor 8-9). The collection had multiple functions: it provided material relief; it demonstrated Gentile solidarity with the Jewish mother church; and — crucially for Paul — it was a live experiment in whether Jewish and Gentile believers could form a single community. Paul\'s anxiety about whether the Jerusalem church would "favorably receive" it (v31) suggests he knew it could be rejected.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Macedonia and Achaia (northern and southern Greece) were provinces whose churches Paul had founded. Their participation in the collection was described in 2 Cor 8:1-5 as an act of grace, overflowing out of extreme poverty. The word translated "contribution" (<em>koinōnian</em>) is the same word used for fellowship/partnership throughout Paul\'s letters (Phil 1:5; 2:1). The collection was not mere charity but an embodied act of <em>koinōnia</em>: a making-common of material resources that mirrored the spiritual fellowship of the one body. The specific identification of "the poor among the Lord\'s people in Jerusalem" likely refers to a group known for their poverty, perhaps connected to the common-purse community described in Acts 2-4.</p>',
    "27": '<p>Paul\'s theological rationale for the collection — "if the Gentiles have shared in Jews\' spiritual blessings, they owe it to the Jews to share with them their material blessings" — draws on a principle of reciprocal obligation. The Greek <em>opheilontai</em> (they are obligated, they owe) is the same word used in 4:4 for wages owed to a worker. But here it is not a commercial debt; it is a covenantal-participation debt. The Gentiles received the gospel, the scriptures, the promises — all mediated through Israel. The material collection is a concrete acknowledgment of that spiritual indebtedness. This was Paul\'s most direct attempt to create a tangible bond between the predominantly Gentile Diaspora churches and the Jerusalem church.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The phrase "completed this task and have made sure they have received this contribution" uses the commercial term <em>sphragisamenos</em> (sealed, certified delivery). In the ancient world, a sealed document or a sealed delivery was certified as properly transacted — the seal provided proof of authentic receipt. Paul\'s use of this term treats the collection as a formal covenant-transaction: its reception by Jerusalem would be the official seal of a completed obligation, after which he would be free to move west. The language reflects not bureaucratic formality but Paul\'s deep investment in the collection\'s success as a theologico-social event.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"Full measure of the blessing of Christ" anticipates that Paul\'s eventual arrival in Rome will be accompanied by the charismatic fullness that the Spirit gives through apostolic ministry. This is a form of the early Christian understanding of apostolic presence: the apostle did not merely deliver information but mediated a spiritual dynamic that built up communities. Paul had not yet visited Rome and could not claim it as his founding; his confidence in coming "with the full measure" is a promise of what apostolic gospel-ministry brings rather than a claim on their allegiance.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The appeal to join in his struggle by prayer uses the athletic-combat term <em>synagonizesthai</em> (to struggle together), which Paul also uses in Col 4:12 for Epaphras\'s prayer life. Prayer was understood in both Jewish and early Christian thought as a form of intercessory combat — genuine spiritual effort on behalf of another person before God. The threefold grounding ("our Lord Jesus Christ and the love of the Spirit") is not merely rhetorical: Paul invokes the relational bonds of the community — their common Lord and the Spirit\'s love — as the basis for their solidarity with him in a dangerous undertaking.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Paul\'s double prayer request — safety from "unbelievers in Judea" and favorable reception of the collection — reveals the genuine danger of his Jerusalem visit. The "unbelievers in Judea" refers to non-Christian Jews who regarded Paul as an apostate and a threat to Jewish community cohesion (cf. Acts 21:20-21, where Jerusalem Jewish Christians themselves are warned that Paul has been accused of teaching Jews to forsake Moses). Acts 21-22 records exactly the hostile reception Paul feared: arrest, riot, near-lynching. His anxiety in this prayer request was prophetically accurate.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The conditional "by God\'s will" (<em>dia thelēmatos theou</em>) is a standard early Christian epistolary formula (cf. Jas 4:15; Acts 18:21) that acknowledges human plans as contingent on divine providence. Paul\'s confidence about his Spain ambitions (v24) is now hedged by this acknowledgment — not because he doubts the gospel\'s advance, but because he knows the Jerusalem visit carries real risk. The "be refreshed in your company" (<em>synanapausomai hymin</em>) is a moment of unusual personal disclosure: Paul is weary and anticipates the Roman congregation as a source of renewal for him, not merely a new church to instruct.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The benediction "God of peace be with you" (<em>ho theos tēs eirēnēs</em>) is the first of several peace-benedictions in Paul\'s letters. "Peace" here carries its full Hebrew <em>shalom</em> register: not absence of conflict but the comprehensive well-being of a rightly-ordered relationship with God. The fact that Paul closes the main body of the letter with this specific attribution — God as peace-giver — is thematically fitting: the entire discussion of chapters 14-15 has been about restoring peace between strong and weak factions. God who is peace is the source of the community peace Paul has been arguing for.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>Phoebe is introduced with two titles: <em>diakonos</em> (minister/deacon) of the church at Cenchreae, and <em>prostatis</em> (patroness/benefactor). Cenchreae was the eastern port of Corinth, a significant commercial harbor. <em>Diakonos</em> was used by Paul for himself and other workers in the mission (1 Cor 3:5; 2 Cor 6:4; Col 1:23); it need not imply a formal office in this early period but does indicate a recognized ministry role. <em>Prostatis</em> (from <em>proistēmi</em>) refers specifically to a civic patron or benefactor — someone who used their financial resources and social standing to support a group. In the Roman system of <em>euergetism</em> (benefaction), a patron who funded a community\'s needs earned formal recognition and informal authority. Phoebe\'s role made her a person of genuine standing, not a minor character.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Paul\'s instruction to "receive her in the Lord in a way worthy of his people" (<em>axios tōn hagiōn</em>) uses the language of worthy reception that reflects the honor-system of hospitality. In the ancient Mediterranean, receiving a traveler "worthily" meant providing appropriate status recognition, lodging, and support. Phoebe was likely the bearer of the letter itself — a role that gave her significant interpretive authority: the letter-carrier was expected to explain and expand on the letter\'s contents in oral presentation. Her role as "benefactor of many, including me" suggests she had provided financial or logistical support for Paul\'s own mission, which would make receiving her well a matter of both hospitality and honoring Paul\'s network.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Prisca (Priscilla) and Aquila were a Jewish-Christian couple who had left Rome under Claudius\'s expulsion (Acts 18:2, c.AD 49) and were now apparently back. Paul had stayed with them in Corinth (Acts 18:3) and worked alongside Aquila as a fellow tentmaker. They are mentioned six times in the NT, and in four of the six occurrences Prisca is named first — unusual in a culture where the husband would typically be named first. This consistent reversal suggests Prisca held greater prominence in the community, whether by social standing, spiritual gift, or both. They had also hosted a church in Ephesus (1 Cor 16:19) and now apparently in Rome again.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"They risked their lives for me" likely refers to an incident in Ephesus (cf. Acts 19:23-41; 1 Cor 15:32, where Paul speaks of "fighting wild beasts in Ephesus"). The specific danger to Paul that Prisca and Aquila helped him escape is unknown, but the acknowledgment that "all the churches of the Gentiles are grateful to them" indicates their service was publicly known across Paul\'s network. In a culture where loyalty to a patron or benefactor in time of danger was one of the highest expressions of the client relationship, their action would have been honored as exemplary.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Epaenetus, the "first convert to Christ in the province of Asia," holds an honorary title: <em>aparchē</em> (firstfruits). In the agricultural metaphor, the firstfruits were the initial portion of the harvest consecrated to God before the rest could be used. Paul uses this same language for entire households (1 Cor 16:15) and for Christ himself (1 Cor 15:20). The designation of Epaenetus as the Asian firstfruits places him in a special relation to the rest of the Asian Christian community — he is the pledge of the larger harvest that followed. That he is now in Rome suggests the mobility of early Christians across the empire\'s commercial networks.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Mary is identified solely by her labor — "she worked very hard for you" (<em>pollā ekopiasas eis hymas</em>). The verb <em>kopiaō</em> (to labor to the point of exhaustion) is the same Paul uses for his own apostolic work and for other recognized workers in the mission (1 Cor 15:10; 1 Thess 5:12; 1 Tim 5:17). This is not casual language for domestic service; it is the vocabulary Paul reserves for missionary and ministerial effort. The fact that Paul acknowledges her labor with this specific vocabulary places Mary in the category of recognized co-workers in the mission, regardless of the specific nature of her service to the Roman community.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Andronicus and Junia are described as "outstanding among the apostles" and "in Christ before I was." The name Junia (<em>Iounian</em>) is almost certainly a woman\'s name — it was common in Rome and unambiguously feminine; the masculine "Junias" is otherwise unattested in ancient sources, and the scholarly consensus has shifted decisively to reading this as a woman. The phrase <em>episēmoi en tois apostolois</em> has been debated: it can mean "outstanding as members of the apostolic circle" or "held in high esteem by the apostles." The first reading implies Junia and Andronicus were themselves apostles in the broader Pauline sense (envoys of the missionary community); the second makes them highly regarded by others who were apostles. Both readings remain defended in scholarship. That they were "in Christ before" Paul situates them as very early believers, possibly converted in the aftermath of Pentecost.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Ampliatus was a common slave name in Rome; a tomb inscription from the Domitilla catacomb (dated to the late first or early second century) reads "Ampliati" in decorative lettering, suggesting the name was associated with the Christian community at Rome from an early period. Whether this is the same Ampliatus cannot be verified, but the inscription shows that a person of this name held sufficient honor in the Roman Christian community to warrant an elaborate burial. Paul\'s address to him as "my dear friend" (<em>agapēton mou en kyriō</em>) is personal and warm — indicating a real prior relationship, not merely a formal acknowledgment.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Urbanus is a Latin name meaning "city man" or "sophisticated" — common among both slaves and freedpersons. The title "our co-worker in Christ" (<em>ton synergon hēmōn en Christō</em>) is Paul\'s standard designation for recognized missionary partners (cf. Priscilla and Aquila in 1 Cor 3:9; Philemon 1). The greeting list as a whole reflects the diverse social composition of the Roman church: Latin names (Urbanus, Rufus, Julia), Greek names (Asyncritus, Phlegon, Hermes), Jewish names (Mary, Andronicus, Junia, Herodion). This diversity mirrors the broader social reality of Rome, where Jewish Diaspora communities lived alongside Greek immigrants and native Romans in a highly stratified but porous social environment.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Apelles is greeted as "the approved in Christ" (<em>ton dokimon en Christō</em>) — a term used for someone tested and proven trustworthy, perhaps a reference to having endured some form of trial or persecution for his faith. The household of Aristobulus is greeted rather than Aristobulus himself, which may indicate that Aristobulus was not himself a believer but that some members of his household were. If this is Aristobulus the grandson of Herod the Great (a historically documented figure in Rome who died around AD 48-49), his household would have included Jewish freedpersons and slaves who could plausibly have encountered the early Roman Christian community.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Herodion is greeted as Paul\'s <em>syngenē</em> (kinsman/fellow Jew), the same term used for Andronicus and Junia. The household of Narcissus appears in a pattern similar to Aristobulus: greetings to believers within the household of a likely non-believing patron. A Narcissus who was a wealthy freedman of Emperor Claudius, influential in Rome until his execution shortly after Nero\'s accession (c.AD 54), is documented by Tacitus and Suetonius. If this identification is correct, the "household of Narcissus" would have been inherited by the imperial household after his death and would have consisted of former slaves now belonging to the emperor\'s estate — precisely the kind of persons who appear in Phil 4:22 ("those who belong to Caesar\'s household").</p>',
    "12": '<p>Tryphena and Tryphosa — likely sisters, given the paired names from the same root (<em>tryphē</em>, luxury or delicacy) — are both described as "working hard in the Lord" using the same <em>kopiaō</em> verb noted for Mary in v6. The name-pair suggests they may have been twins or siblings who were known as a unit in the community. Persis, "the beloved," is distinguished from them by the past tense of her labor ("she worked very hard"), which may indicate advanced age or retirement from active service. The cluster of women laborers in this greeting list — Mary (v6), Tryphena, Tryphosa, Persis, and Junia (v7) — is notable: Paul\'s network of co-workers included a significant number of women in recognized ministerial roles.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Rufus is "chosen in the Lord" (<em>eklekton en kyriō</em>) — a title that in this context likely reflects outstanding faith or distinguished service rather than making a specific election-theology claim. Mark 15:21 identifies Simon of Cyrene as "the father of Alexander and Rufus," and if the Roman congregation knew this Rufus as Simon\'s son, the reference would carry the weight of family association with the Passion narrative itself. That his mother "has been a mother to me too" is one of Paul\'s most personal disclosures in the letter: at some point, this unnamed woman had cared for Paul with maternal care — lodging him, feeding him, nursing him in illness, or simply providing the kind of domestic stability that a traveling apostle lacked.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Asyncritus, Phlegon, Hermes, Patrobas, and Hermas are all Greek names, several of which were common among slaves and freedpersons. The reference to "the brothers and sisters with them" suggests these five men formed the leadership or core of a distinct house-church unit. The Roman congregation was not a single gathering but a network of house-churches meeting in the homes of those with sufficient space (cf. v5, Prisca and Aquila\'s house; v14, this group; v15, another group). Each house-church would have had its own social character, possibly with distinct ethnic compositions reflecting the host household.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Philologus, Julia, Nereus, his sister, and Olympas represent another house-church cluster. Julia was among the most common women\'s names in Rome, often carried by slaves and freedpersons with connections to the Julian imperial family. The inclusion of Nereus\'s unnamed sister reflects a reality of ancient letter-writing: Paul greets individuals by name and whole groups by reference, but women\'s secondary status in public record-keeping often meant they were identified by relation to a male relative rather than by their own names. The "all the Lord\'s people who are with them" follows the same house-church pattern as v14.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The holy kiss (<em>philēma hagion</em>) was the standard Mediterranean greeting gesture — a kiss on the cheek or forehead — that the early Christian communities adopted as a formalized liturgical greeting. Justin Martyr (c.AD 150) describes it as part of the weekly Eucharistic gathering: "When we have ended the prayers, we greet one another with a kiss" (<em>First Apology</em> 65). In the context of a community divided between strong and weak, Jew and Gentile, slave and free, the commanded mutual kiss across those social boundaries was itself a social declaration of unity. The greeting "all the churches of Christ send greetings" implies Paul speaks with the authority of the entire apostolic network.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The warning against "those who cause divisions and put obstacles in your way contrary to the teaching you have learned" echoes the language of the strong/weak controversy just resolved in chs14-15, but now refers to external teachers rather than internal differences. The Roman congregation had received a specific body of teaching (<em>didachē</em>) — likely the oral gospel tradition and the ethical instruction that Paul himself summarizes in chs12-15. Teachers who deviate from this pattern are to be avoided, not engaged: the instruction is social separation, not extended debate. In a community without formal institutional authority, the shared tradition itself was the standard against which deviant teaching could be measured.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The description of the divisive teachers as serving "their own appetites" (<em>tē heautōn koiliai douleuousin</em>) — literally "their own belly" — picks up the food-controversy language of ch14 in a satirical register: while the community had been wrestling with genuine questions about what to eat, these teachers make their own desires the rule. The charge of smooth speech and flattery (<em>chrēstologia kai eulogia</em>) against naive people reflects the Greco-Roman rhetorical critique of the sophist: the skilled but unprincipled speaker who persuades through technique rather than truth. In a community accustomed to the honor-competition of public rhetoric, this was a recognizable and serious accusation.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Paul\'s grounding of the warning in the community\'s known obedience (<em>hē hypakoē hymōn</em>) mirrors the letter\'s opening (1:8, "your faith is being reported all over the world"). Their reputation for faithful obedience was itself a social asset — communities in the ancient world were known by their reputation across the network of travelers, merchants, and church messengers who connected the cities. The instruction to be "wise about what is good, and innocent about what is evil" (<em>sophous eis to agathon, akeraious eis to kakon</em>) echoes Jesus\'s commission in Matt 10:16 ("wise as serpents, innocent as doves"), suggesting Paul was drawing on a known dominical saying.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"The God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet" is a direct allusion to Gen 3:15 (the protoevangelium): "I will put enmity between you and the woman, and between your offspring and hers; he will crush your head." Paul applies what was a promise about the seed of the woman to the community collectively: through their faithfulness and unity, they participate in the eschatological defeat of the adversary. The "soon" (<em>en tachei</em>) is eschatological urgency, not a literal timetable prediction. The form of the promise ("God of peace will crush") deliberately echoes the "God of peace" benediction of 15:33, creating a frame around the greeting section.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Timothy is mentioned here as a fellow-worker sending greetings — he was with Paul in Corinth during the writing of the letter (Acts 20:4 places him in the party that traveled with Paul to Jerusalem). Lucius, Jason, and Sosipater are identified as Paul\'s <em>syngeneis</em> (fellow Jews). Jason may be the Jason of Thessalonica who hosted Paul and was dragged before the city authorities (Acts 17:5-9); Sosipater may be the Sopater of Beroea listed in Paul\'s travel party in Acts 20:4. If so, the greeting list connects the letter with the same journey that ended in Paul\'s arrest — making these greetings not just farewell pleasantries but the voices of people walking with Paul toward Jerusalem.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Tertius is the letter\'s <em>amanuensis</em> (secretary): Paul dictated and Tertius wrote. This was standard practice in the ancient world for extended documents — even literate authors frequently used trained scribes for correspondence, and the secretary\'s handwriting could be as important as his speed and accuracy. The fact that Tertius adds his own greeting "in the Lord" is unusual (most secretaries remained anonymous in ancient letters) and suggests he was a known member of the early Christian community, not merely a professional scribe. Galatians 6:11 ("see with what large letters I write with my own hand") indicates Paul sometimes did write autographically for at least the closing of his letters; Romans appears to have been entirely dictated except perhaps for any final personal signature.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Gaius, "whose hospitality I and the whole church here enjoy," was a man of sufficient means to host both Paul and the full congregation of the Corinthian church — a large house with a reception room (<em>triclinium</em>) capable of accommodating a community gathering. This Gaius is likely the Gaius Paul baptized in 1 Cor 1:14. Erastus is identified as the <em>oikonomos</em> (steward or director of public works) of Corinth — a civic office of significant standing. A paving-stone inscription found during 1929 excavations in Corinth reads: "Erastus, in return for the aedileship, laid this pavement at his own expense" — the aedile was a civic official responsible for public buildings and streets. If this is the same person, he was a prominent public figure in Corinth who was also a believer.</p>',
    "24": '<p>This verse is absent from the best manuscripts (P46, Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and is likely a scribal addition; it repeats the grace-benediction of v20. Its presence in some manuscript traditions reflects early liturgical practice of adding or moving benedictions to close individual sections or ensure the letter ended with a doxological flourish. For the Roman congregation receiving this letter, the text as they knew it may or may not have included this verse depending on which manuscript tradition reached them.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The closing doxology (vv25-27) addresses "the one who is able to establish you" — a description of God as the one who makes the community stable and firm (<em>stērixai</em>, to establish, confirm). The "mystery hidden for long ages past" (<em>mustērion chronois aiōniois sesigēmenon</em>) uses the technical vocabulary of the mystery genre: in Daniel, <em>rāz</em> (mystery) refers to divine secrets disclosed to the wise; in the Qumran texts, the community received the <em>razê El</em> (mysteries of God) not available to outsiders. Paul\'s claim is that the mystery of the gospel — Gentile inclusion through Christ — is this long-hidden divine secret now revealed. The doxology functions as both worship and summary: the letter that has been about this mystery ends with praise to the God who authored it.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"Now revealed and made known through the prophetic writings by the command of the eternal God" brings together two elements: the OT witness (the prophetic scriptures) and the apostolic mission (for the obedience of faith among all nations). The prophetic scriptures are not merely predictions now fulfilled; they are the very disclosure mechanism — the Scriptures themselves contain the mystery, now readable in light of Christ. This is the hermeneutical principle Paul has enacted throughout the letter: citing the Torah (Gen 15:6), the Psalms (Ps 32, 69, 117), the Prophets (Isa 52:15), to show that the Gentile gospel was always latent in Israel\'s scriptures. The "obedience of faith among all nations" echoes 1:5, forming a frame around the entire letter.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The doxology\'s final phrase — "to the only wise God be glory forever through Jesus Christ, Amen" — closes the letter as it opened: with the God of Israel, the God of the gospel, the God who has been just in justifying the ungodly (3:26). The attribution of wisdom to God alone (<em>monō sophō theō</em>) may carry a polemical edge: in the Greco-Roman world, wisdom was an attribute claimed for philosophers, mystery-religion initiates, and imperial propaganda. Paul locates authentic wisdom in the God whose mystery has been hidden in Israel\'s scriptures and is now disclosed in the crucified and risen Christ — the "wisdom of God" that Paul has already described as appearing foolish to human evaluation (1 Cor 1:24-25). The letter ends where it began: in the praise of this God.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'romans')
    merge_comm(existing, ROMANS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'romans', existing)
    print('Romans 15–16 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
